    "intro": "Interpretation asks what the text means — moving from observation (what does it say?) to discerning the author's intent in his original context, and then placing that meaning within the psalm's canonical and Messianic frame. Psalm 144 is a royal war psalm that doubles as a covenant-blessing liturgy. Its four movements are not loosely connected; they form a theological argument about the relationship between God's identity, human fragility, divine intervention, and national flourishing. The Messianic dimension — unmistakable in the later development of 'David his servant' as the prototype of the coming king — is noted where the text warrants it.",
